      "summary": "Artifact identity, location, and lifecycle are not defined consistently across the role, contract, and completion rules.",
      "severity": "blocking",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f1",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "The canonical role artifacts are named generically in <outputs> using <slug>-prefixed filenames, but the required canonical paths identified by self-check are full package paths under tools/agent-role-builder/role/. The package therefore does not state the actual freeze targets unambiguously.",
          "source_section": "<outputs>; Self-check issues"
        },
        {
          "id": "f2",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "The contract summary's package_files uses bare filenames (for example agent-role-builder-role.md) rather than the canonical package paths expected by self-check, so the markdown and contract do not identify the same output locations.",
          "source_section": "Contract summary.package_files; Self-check issues"
        },
        {
          "id": "f3",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Step 5 says decision log, board summary, and result.json are written during resolve/promote, but <outputs> marks decision log and board summary as canonical artifacts promoted on freeze, and <completion> only requires the decision log to be updated on freeze. This leaves non-frozen runs underspecified for whether those artifacts exist, where they live, and whether they are draft, evidence, or canonical outputs.",
          "source_section": "<steps> Step 5; <outputs>; <completion>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Define one authoritative artifact map with exact relative paths and lifecycle states for every artifact. Use the same paths in <steps>, <outputs>, <completion>, and contract package_files. Separate clearly between draft/internal/evidence/canonical artifacts and state which artifacts must exist for frozen versus non-frozen terminal states."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-2",
      "summary": "Scope and boundary text is directionally correct but duplicated in ways that weaken structural coherence.",
      "severity": "minor",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f4",
          "severity": "minor",
          "description": "The not-in-scope list repeats 'Application workflow creation' and repeats 'Application runtime orchestration' with slightly different wording. The intended boundary is understandable, but the duplication makes the scope section look unstable.",
          "source_section": "<scope>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f5",
          "severity": "minor",
          "description": "Board-review orchestration is described as owned 'within this tool' in <authority> and as the only in-scope exception to runtime orchestration in <scope>, but the distinction is spread across multiple bullets instead of being stated once as a single clean boundary.",
          "source_section": "<authority>; <scope>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Collapse duplicate exclusions and restate the orchestration boundary once: board-review orchestration for role-package governance is in scope; broader application runtime orchestration is out of scope."
    }
  ],
  "residual_risks": [
    "The contract summary does not visibly encode roster composition requirements as explicitly as the markdown guardrails, which can allow future drift between contract validation and role behavior.",
    "The split-verdict and arbitration flow is reasonably described, but the artifact model for recording arbitration outcomes is still implicit rather than explicitly tied to a named output."
  ],
  "strengths": [
    "Required role tags are present and the overall section structure is coherent.",
    "Authority is mostly well-bounded: tool creation, code execution, and broader runtime orchestration are explicitly excluded.",
    "Guardrails are strong on non-invention, non-expansion of authority, provenance, and freeze discipline.",
    "The review loop includes clear non-freeze conditions for mixed verdicts and unresolved material pushback."
  ]
}

